00:16:31,800 --> 00:16:36,120
That makes so much sense. We're talking about 
cultural elements and so I have one more question  

182
00:16:36,120 --> 00:16:42,400
around culture. I saw a video interview you did 
once about how you love this concept of giving  

183
00:16:42,400 --> 00:16:48,240
away your Legos, that's part of your culture 
and the culture at Canva broadly potentially,  

184
00:16:48,240 --> 00:16:53,480
and this was originally popularized by Molly 
Graham in this first round review article. That's  

185
00:16:53,480 --> 00:16:58,080
something you still believe in and if so, can you 
just describe that concept briefly because a lot  

186
00:16:58,080 --> 00:17:02,360
of people haven't actually heard about this?
Yeah, Molly wrote a great article, which I  

187
00:17:02,360 --> 00:17:08,840
actually refer everyone who joins Canva to in 
the cultural onboarding session, which I give  

188
00:17:08,840 --> 00:17:14,480
them. So I run everyone through the culture at 
Canva and what they can expect over the next few  

189
00:17:14,480 --> 00:17:19,160
years as they work here, and one of those sections 
is on giving away your Lego, and it's really  

190
00:17:19,160 --> 00:17:25,600
important to us because part of being in a startup 
is scaling, when you're scaling from zero users  

191
00:17:25,600 --> 00:17:32,680
to a million to a hundred million, and when you're 
scaling from three founders to 10 employees to 100  

192
00:17:32,680 --> 00:17:38,400
employees to 4,000 employees. You're scaling 
everything from the product to the internal  

193
00:17:38,400 --> 00:17:45,080
processes you have, the finance team paying people 
how you deal with user feedback. Everything's just  

194
00:17:45,080 --> 00:17:51,200
constantly growing, growing, growing. And I think 
this is slightly different to a traditional job  

195
00:17:51,200 --> 00:17:55,880
where you get good at the thing that you 
always do and you try and turn that into a  

196
00:17:55,880 --> 00:18:01,320
process that just continually works all the time.
As a startup, you just have to be changing and we  

197
00:18:01,320 --> 00:18:06,640
want people who are flexible, you can bring 
new ideas, you can go to that next level. You  

198
00:18:06,640 --> 00:18:10,960
can think about not just a million people, 
but 10 million people, 100 million people,  

199
00:18:10,960 --> 00:18:17,040
a billion people using the product, and 
to constantly ratchet up that multiplier,  

200
00:18:17,040 --> 00:18:22,960
you need to change yourself, which means that you 
probably need to give away some of the stuff that  

201
00:18:22,960 --> 00:18:27,520
you're doing now in order to get to that next 
level. If you're the first email copywriter  

202
00:18:27,520 --> 00:18:33,360
at Canva, you can get away from writing all the 
emails for the first year maybe, but when you're  

203
00:18:33,360 --> 00:18:39,760
writing emails for 100 million people in 190 
different countries, in 100 different languages,  

204
00:18:39,760 --> 00:18:45,880
all at different stages of their journey through 
using Canva from beginners to intermediates to  

205
00:18:45,880 --> 00:18:51,440
experts, that just massively multiplies the 
complexity of the job that you have to do.  

206
00:18:51,440 --> 00:18:55,880
And if you're trying to write every single one 
of those emails, you have no chance of scaling.
 

207
00:18:55,880 --> 00:19:00,000
So you need to think about who you're going to 
bring in to help you, what systems you're going  

208
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:04,920
to introduce, what are the processes needed to get 
100 different languages translated every time you  

209
00:19:04,920 --> 00:19:11,200
send out an email and that requires you to hand 
off that stuff. You need to maybe stop writing  

210
00:19:11,200 --> 00:19:16,760
every single email, give that to someone else, 
be comfortable with doing that because you often  

211
00:19:16,760 --> 00:19:20,720
build up a lot of self-identity and doing that 
and you get a lot of joy out of it. That's why  

212
00:19:20,720 --> 00:19:25,280
you're a writer in the first place. But finding 
joy in the other things of building a team,  

213
00:19:25,280 --> 00:19:30,200
passing on your experience, helping other people 
do great writing or great product building or  

214
00:19:30,200 --> 00:19:35,240
great engineering is really what giving away 
your Lego is about. And we still encourage  

215
00:19:35,240 --> 00:19:40,800
everyone to do that, to think about those moments 
where they need to level up in their impact,  

216
00:19:40,800 --> 00:19:44,480
how they can bring their team along with 
them, how they can pass on their experience  

217
00:19:44,480 --> 00:19:50,920
and help everyone really have a tremendous 
impact with the skills that they have.
 

218
00:19:50,920 --> 00:19:55,320
I think a lot of people and a lot of companies 
struggle with this idea, and I'm curious if  

219
00:19:55,320 --> 00:19:58,800
there's something you've learned about how to 
actually implement this. Is it just like, "Hey,  

220
00:19:58,800 --> 00:20:02,080
go read this article and then I might bring it up 
sometimes when things are changing and there's a  

221
00:20:02,080 --> 00:20:07,000
reorg."? Or is there anything even deeper of just 
this is a cultural element of we are constantly  

222
00:20:07,000 --> 00:20:12,640
giving up our Lego's giving things that we own?
Probably the deeper thing I think is giving people  

223
00:20:12,640 --> 00:20:18,120
opportunity so you can talk about growth 
than just say, "Please grow." That's not  

224
00:20:18,120 --> 00:20:23,680
going to be terribly effective, but giving 
them the opportunity and the support to do so  

225
00:20:23,680 --> 00:20:28,240
is super important. We have a system we call 
coaching at Canva where you have a coach and  

226
00:20:28,240 --> 00:20:33,080
they're constantly working with you to look at 
your skills, how you can improve each of those  

227
00:20:33,080 --> 00:20:38,320
individual skills, but also what it is that you're 
actually doing and when it might be the time  

228
00:20:38,320 --> 00:20:43,640
to move on to the next level. Say you are just 
doing a product role in this particular product  

229
00:20:43,640 --> 00:20:49,320
and now you need to be a coach of other product 
managers and help build products. Understanding  

230
00:20:49,320 --> 00:20:53,920
those pivot points is really important and our 
coaches help everyone at Canva. Everyone at  

231
00:20:53,920 --> 00:21:00,480
Canva has a coach that is constantly thinking 
about this aspect of their personal growth.
 

232
00:21:00,480 --> 00:21:05,400
And finding those opportunities where you can 
push someone to do something that they haven't  

233
00:21:05,400 --> 00:21:11,640
done before or to expand upon an idea that they've 
had and give them ownership of that idea is super  

234
00:21:11,640 --> 00:21:16,760
important. So when people do come to us with an 
amazing product idea or a feature that they want  

235
00:21:16,760 --> 00:21:22,680
to build or an entire team that they think 
should be spun up, we really listen to them,  

236
00:21:22,680 --> 00:21:29,080
and if it makes sense, we say, "Go and do that. Go 
and build that part of the product, grab a couple  

237
00:21:29,080 --> 00:21:34,480
of people and start building video at Canva. 
Do that thing that you're talking about." And  

238
00:21:34,480 --> 00:21:39,320
I think if you give them the opportunity and 
a little push to go beyond what they think  

239
00:21:39,320 --> 00:21:44,920
they're comfortable with right now, that is 
the best way to drive growth in your team.
 

240
00:21:44,920 --> 00:21:48,280
Okay. There's two things I want to follow up 
on there. One is this coaching concept. I've  

241
00:21:48,280 --> 00:21:52,320
never heard of this. So how does that 
work? Do they have a manager and they  

242
00:21:52,320 --> 00:21:58,720
have coach, and who is this coach?
We don't really have managers. So your  

243
00:21:58,720 --> 00:22:04,960
coach is the person who thinks about you in 
a specialty sense. So we have specialties,  

244
00:22:04,960 --> 00:22:10,840
engineering, product design, we got tens 
of different specialties across Canva, and  

245
00:22:10,840 --> 00:22:17,000
your coach really helps.. Your coach is a similar 
specialty leads, so if you're a product manager,  

246
00:22:17,000 --> 00:22:23,600
they're a product manager, so they know the skills 
that you have to use. They know the trajectory  

247
00:22:23,600 --> 00:22:27,440
that you could possibly grow into. They know the 
structures that are around Canva that you could  

248
00:22:27,440 --> 00:22:33,120
slot into when you want to go to the next level. 
And your coach constantly checks in with you,  

249
00:22:33,120 --> 00:22:38,280
has sessions, might help you with the strategy 
doc, might have a one-on-one with you. They  

250
00:22:38,280 --> 00:22:42,920
just constantly thinking about those ways 
that you can grow and improve at Canva.
 

251
00:22:42,920 --> 00:22:51,160
And then we have probably more of a, I would 
say, collegiate managerial circle of colleagues  

252
00:22:51,160 --> 00:22:57,520
who help you who do 360 feedback, all that kind of 
stuff. So that's the structure that we've arrived  

253
00:22:57,520 --> 00:23:02,960
on and it's worked pretty well for us and it was 
driven actually by a formative coaching experience  

254
00:23:02,960 --> 00:23:07,520
that we had as founders quite a few years ago 
from an external coach and we decided to bring  

255
00:23:07,520 --> 00:23:11,680
that into Canva as a whole philosophy.
And these coaches, are they professional  

256
00:23:11,680 --> 00:23:15,720
coaches or they're people in the company that are 
like, "I will be a coach for this function."?
 

257
00:23:15,720 --> 00:23:21,920
They're people in the company. So we've got 
probably close to 800 or 1,000 coaches now  

258
00:23:21,920 --> 00:23:23,320
at Canva.
Wow.
 

259
00:23:23,320 --> 00:23:29,600
We do have very specific coaches who are just 
coaches and they can drop into any situation.  

260
00:23:29,600 --> 00:23:33,560
They're not product managers, they're not 
designers, but they're relatively few. I think,  

261
00:23:33,560 --> 00:23:40,440
we've got probably five of those type of coaches 
and they just work in very special situations,  

262
00:23:40,440 --> 00:23:46,320
but what we're focused on is enabling the 
broader circle of coaches, so those 800  

263
00:23:46,320 --> 00:23:51,200
people to understand what it is to be a coach 
and have the skills of coaching. So we focus  

264
00:23:51,200 --> 00:23:59,200
a lot on teaching them the skills of coaching, 
how to build a growth mindset in their coaches,  

265
00:23:59,200 --> 00:24:02,880
all the skills that you need. So 
yeah, it's a massive part of Canva.
 

266
00:24:02,880 --> 00:24:07,280
And so there's a product management coach and 
this person helps all the PMs become better at  

267
00:24:07,280 --> 00:24:09,640
the craft of product management.
Yeah.
 

268
00:24:09,640 --> 00:24:13,560
Wow, so interesting. Okay, and then the 
performance review piece, how does that work?
 

